\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Mohs Scale of Science Fiction Hardness\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb180\sa180\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpeculativeFiction"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf2 Speculative Fiction}}
\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0  fanatics are always raving about how \'93hard\'94 the science is in various stories \'97 but it\'92s not like you can rub 
\f2\i a story
\f1\i0  with a piece of quartz and see if it leaves a scratch on 
\f2\i the plot
\f1\i0 . So what is \'93hardness\'94 in SF? Why do some people want it? And {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SortingAlgorithmOfTropes"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 how do we put a number to it}}?\
Beginning with the first question: \'93Hard\'94 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceFiction"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Science Fiction}} is firmly grounded in reality, with only a few fantastic flights of fancy not justified by science, or with the technology being nonexistent in today\'92s world but probably scientifically possible at some point. \'93Soft\'94 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SciFi"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Sci-Fi}} is more flexible on the rules. Even the fantastical aspects of the story will show a divide \'97 in hard SF, they operate through strict, preferably physical, laws, where in soft SF they work in whatever way suits the story best. What this leads to for hard SF is a raised bar for the amount of scientific research the writer must put into the story, and usually {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ShownTheirWork"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 this is shown quite clearly}}.\
Example: a character is shown a time machine and asks, \'93How does it work?\'94\
\pard\tx0\pardeftab720\li480\fi-480\sl360\slmult1\sb36\sa36\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \'95	
\f3\b In soft SF:
\f1\b0  \'93You sit in this seat, set the date you want, and pull that lever.\'94\
\'95	
\f3\b In hard SF:
\f1\b0  \'93A good question with an interesting answer. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Infodump"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Please have a seat while I bring you up to speed}} on the latest ideas in quantum theory, after which I will spend a chapter detailing an elaborate, yet plausible-sounding connection between quantum states, the unified field theory, and the means by which the brain stores memory, all tied into theories from both {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/AlbertEinstein"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Albert Einstein}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SmallReferencePools"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 and}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/StephenHawking"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Stephen Hawking}}.\'94\
\'95	
\f3\b In really hard SF:
\f1\b0  \'93It doesn\'92t. Time travel to the past is impossible.\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb180\sa180\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Unfortunately for analytical purposes, this pattern is not universal - hard SF stories can skip over the details as long as the basic explanation is correct {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MagicAIsMagicA"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 given what\'92s been established so far}}. Therefore, regardless of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://archive.is/9HERI"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 typical stylistic flourishes}} (\'93If all stories were written like science fiction stories\'94 by Mark Rosenfelder, a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ConLang"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 conlanger}}) of hard SF, the only way to define it is self-consistency and scientific accuracy.\
Which leads us to the Scale.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 1. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Mohs/ScienceInGenreOnly"}}{\fldrslt Science in Genre Only}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb180\sa180\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 The work is unambiguously set in the 
\f2\i literary genre
\f1\i0  of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceFiction"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Science Fiction}}, but 
\f2\i scientific
\f1\i0  it is not. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AppliedPhlebotinum"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Applied Phlebotinum}} is the rule of the day, often of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ItRunsOnNonsensoleum"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Nonsensoleum}} kind, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GreenRocks"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Green Rocks}} gain {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NewPowersAsThePlotDemands"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 New Powers as the Plot Demands}}, and both {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BellisariosMaxim"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Bellisario\'92s Maxim}} and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MST3KMantra"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 MST3K Mantra}} apply. Works like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/Futurama"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Futurama}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/StarWars"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Star Wars}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/TengenToppaGurrenLagann"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Tengen Toppa Gurren Lagann}}, The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/DCComics"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 DC}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/MarvelComics"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Marvel}} universes, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/TheHitchhikersGuideToTheGalaxy"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 The Hitchhiker\'92s Guide to the Galaxy}} fall in this class.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 2. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Mohs/WorldOfPhlebotinum"}}{\fldrslt World of Phlebotinum}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb180\sa180\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 The universe is full of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AppliedPhlebotinum"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Applied Phlebotinum}} with more to be found behind every star, but the Phlebotinum is dealt with in a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MagicAIsMagicA"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 fairly consistent fashion despite its lack of correspondence with reality}} and, in-world, is considered to lie within the realm of scientific inquiry. Works like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/EEDocSmith"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 E. E. \'93Doc\'94 Smith}}\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Lensman"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Lensman}} series, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/NeonGenesisEvangelion"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Neon Genesis Evangelion}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/StarTrekTheOriginalSeries"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Star Trek: The Original Series}}, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/StarCraft"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 StarCraft}} fall in this category. A subclass of this class (arguably 2.5 on the scale) contains stories that are generally sound, except the physics aren\'92t our own. Plot aside, they are often a philosophical exploration of a concept {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceMarchesOn"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 no longer considered true}} (such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/Aristotle"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Aristotelian physics}}), or never considered true in the first place (e.g.\'a0two spatial dimensions instead of three, like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Flatland"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Flatland}}). Some of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/ArthurCClarke"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Arthur C. Clarke}}\'92s stories fall here. However, given {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceFantasy"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 the overlap with fantasy}}, it can {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GenreBusting"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 prove tricky}} to even classify a story as SF.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 3. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Mohs/PhysicsPlus"}}{\fldrslt Physics Plus}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb180\sa180\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 Stories in this class once again have multiple forms of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AppliedPhlebotinum"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Applied Phlebotinum}}, but in contrast to the prior class, the author aims to justify these creations with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ShownTheirWork"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 real}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MinovskyParticle"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 invented}} natural laws \'97 and these creations and others from the same laws will {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ChekhovsBoomerang"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 turn up again and again in new contexts}}. Works like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/SchlockMercenary"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Schlock Mercenary}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/DavidWeber"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 David Weber}}\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/HonorHarrington"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Honor Harrington}} series, David Brin\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Uplift"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Uplift}} series, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/BattlestarGalactica2003"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Battlestar Galactica (2003)}} fall in this class. Most {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RealRobot"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Real Robot}} shows fall somewhere between Classes 2 and 3.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 4. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Mohs/OneBigLie"}}{\fldrslt One Big Lie}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb180\sa180\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 Authors of works in this class invent one (or, at most, a very few) counterfactual physical laws and writes a story that explores the implications of these principles. James Blish\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/CitiesInFlight"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Cities in Flight}} stories fall squarely into this category, courtesy of the \'93Dirac Equations\'94 leading to the \'93spindizzy motor\'94 and instantaneous communication. Most works in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/AlanDeanFoster"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Alan Dean Foster}}\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/HumanxCommonwealth"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Humanx Commonwealth}} series, the Ad Astra board games and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/RobertAHeinlein"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Robert A. Heinlein}}\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/FarnhamsFreehold"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Farnham\'92s Freehold}} fall in this category, as do many of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/VernorVinge"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Vernor Vinge}}\'92s books. This class also includes a subclass (4.5 on the scale) we call 
\f2\i One Small Fib
\f1\i0 , containing stories that include only a single counterfactual device (often {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FTLTravel"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 FTL Travel}}), but for which the device is not a major element of the plot. Many {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/HalClement"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Hal Clement}} novels (e.g.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/MissionOfGravity"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Mission of Gravity}}, 
\f2\i Close to Critical
\f1\i0 ) and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Freefall"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf2 Freefall}} fall within the subclass.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 5. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Mohs/SpeculativeScience"}}{\fldrslt Speculative Science}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb180\sa180\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 Stories in which there is no \'93big lie\'94 \'97 the science of the tale is (or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScienceMarchesOn"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 was}}) genuine speculative science or engineering, and the goal of the author to make as few errors with respect to known fact as possible. The first two books in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/RobertLForward"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Robert L. Forward}}\'92s 
\f2\i Rocheworld
